<h2 class="page_heading">Searching with Sphinx &amp; Heroku Connect</h2>
<h3>About the project</h3>
<p>This starter project demonstrates the following technologies:</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <h4>Sphinx search</h4>
    <p><%= link_to('Sphinx', 'http://sphinxsearch.com/', title: 'Find out more') %>
       offers powerful search engine that, thanks to the
       <%= link_to('ThinkingSphinx gem', 'http://pat.github.io/thinking-sphinx/', title: 'Find out more') %>,
       provides excellent Rails integration. This project makes use of the
       <%= link_to('FlyingSphinx add-on', 'http://info.flying-sphinx.com/', title: 'Find out more') %>
      to provide ThinkingSphinx functionality on Heroku.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <h4>Heroku Connect</h4>
    <p>The <%= link_to('Heroku Connect add-on', 'https://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/herokuconnect', title: 'Find out more') %>
       allows data from a Salesforce organisation to be shared with an app. In addition to providing
       basic CRUD operations on data provided via Connect, this project also demonstrates how the data can be made searchable
       using Sphinx.</p>
  </li>
</ul>
<h3>Data types</h3>
<p>The following data types are available:</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <h4><%= link_to('Companies', companies_path) %></h4>
    <p>Companies demonstrate how Sphinx works with standard database records.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <h4><%= link_to('Contacts', contacts_path) %></h4>
    <p>Contacts are provided via Heroku Connect and demonstrate how Sphinx can be used to search the data sync'd with Salesforce.</p>
  </li>
</ul>
